---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
const data = {
  metaTitle: "NFT Marketplace for Australian Artists | All Webbed Labs",
  metaDescription: "How we built a Polygon-based NFT marketplace for an 85-member Melbourne arts collective, replacing 50% gallery commissions with a 2.5% platform fee and generating $340K in primary sales in the first 3 months.",

  industry: "Web3 & Crypto",
  tags: ["Smart Contracts", "NFT", "Solidity", "Polygon", "IPFS"],

  title: "NFT Marketplace for Australian Artists",
  summary: "An 85-member Melbourne contemporary arts collective wanted to explore digital ownership for their artwork editions — without surrendering half their revenue to gallery intermediaries. We built them a Polygon-based NFT marketplace with on-chain royalties, IPFS-pinned artwork storage, and a wallet-first buying experience that connected them with international collectors.",

  heroImageDescription: "Artist browsing a dark-mode NFT gallery interface showing artwork editions with edition counts, current owners, and royalty percentages displayed on artwork cards",

  clientOverview: "Placeholder Arts Collective is a Melbourne-based contemporary arts group with 85 member artists working across painting, photography, printmaking and digital media. The collective had been operating for over a decade, selling limited-edition prints and originals through a curated gallery arrangement. They approached us after several members had heard about NFTs through international artist communities and wanted an honest assessment of whether the technology could solve real problems for them — or whether it was hype.",
  clientSize: "85 member artists",
  clientLocation: "Melbourne, VIC",

  pullQuote: "We'd been burned by promises before. What we needed was someone who could tell us what blockchain actually couldn't do, not just what it could. The royalty mechanism alone has paid for the platform three times over.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Sarah K.",
  pullQuoteRole: "Collective Director, Placeholder Arts Collective",

  challenge: [
    "The collective was operating on a traditional gallery consignment model. For every sale, the gallery retained 50% of the sale price — a standard arrangement in the Australian art market but one that left artists with little margin after materials and studio costs. For a $2,000 print, the artist received $1,000. There was no mechanism whatsoever for artists to benefit from secondary market appreciation: if a collector later sold that print for $8,000, the artist received nothing.",
    "International buyers were a real opportunity — the collective had inquiries from buyers in the US, UK, Germany and Singapore — but the friction was enormous. International wire transfers, currency conversion, minimum bank fees, and processing delays of 3–5 business days meant that small purchases (under $500) were often abandoned. The gallery handled currency conversion at rates that weren't transparent to artists.",
    "The collective had zero technical expertise in blockchain, and had been approached by several vendors making claims they couldn't evaluate. One vendor had proposed a custom blockchain solution with ongoing licence fees. Another was recommending Ethereum mainnet at a time when gas fees were running $40–80 per transaction, which would have made $300 artwork editions economically unviable. The collective needed someone willing to give them an honest technology assessment, not a sales pitch.",
    "There was also a legitimate concern about ASIC regulatory positioning. The collective wanted to ensure that selling digital artwork as NFTs didn't inadvertently create a managed investment scheme or financial product offering under the Corporations Act 2001. The line between a collectible and a financial product has regulatory consequences in Australia, and this needed to be addressed upfront, not as an afterthought.",
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The collective was referred to us by an independent Melbourne creative agency who had seen our work on a previous blockchain project. What differentiated us in the initial conversation wasn't enthusiasm about NFTs — it was the opposite. We walked them through scenarios where NFT marketplaces had failed for artists: high gas fees destroying margins, rug-pull platforms abandoning projects, wallet UX alienating non-technical buyers, and the very real risk of building on a network with uncertain long-term liquidity.",
    "We recommended Polygon over Ethereum mainnet specifically because sub-cent gas fees made selling $200–$500 artwork editions viable, and we were transparent about the trade-offs: Polygon has less liquidity than Ethereum mainnet and slightly different security assumptions. We told them this before they engaged us.",
    "We also flagged the ASIC consideration proactively and recommended they obtain a legal opinion from a commercial lawyer with cryptocurrency experience before we wrote a line of code. This added two weeks and some cost to the project, but it meant they launched with confidence rather than hope.",
  ],

  approach: [
    "We started with a two-week discovery phase focused entirely on understanding how artists in the collective actually wanted to interact with the platform. Not all 85 members were technically confident. Some were in their 60s and had never owned cryptocurrency. The platform needed to work for them as sellers, not just for crypto-native buyers.",
    "We conducted workshops with a sample of 12 artists covering: how they currently priced editions, what information buyers typically asked for, their concerns about digital reproduction and provenance, and what 'owning' a digital artwork meant to them philosophically. This research directly shaped the contract architecture: we chose ERC-721 (unique tokens, not fungible) over ERC-1155 (semi-fungible editions) because artists felt strongly that each edition should be individually identifiable and transferable, even within a numbered series.",
    "For the regulatory question, we worked with the collective's appointed commercial lawyer to draft a clear legal disclaimer framework. The key distinction under Australian law is that an NFT representing a digital artwork (a collectible) is treated differently from an NFT representing a fractional interest in an underlying asset with an expectation of financial return (which would potentially be a financial product). Ensuring the platform's design, marketing language and smart contracts reflected a collectible-first model — not an investment product — was essential to maintaining that distinction.",
    "Smart contract architecture was designed before frontend work began. The contract audit scope and test coverage targets were defined upfront, not bolted on at the end. We used Hardhat for the development environment and testing, writing 94 unit tests covering normal mint paths, royalty distribution, batch operations, and edge cases including zero-address transfers and reentrancy attempts.",
  ],

  solution: [
    "The core of the platform is a Solidity smart contract implementing ERC-721 for unique token identity with ERC-2981 for on-chain royalty signalling. ERC-2981 is the royalty standard that major marketplaces — OpenSea, Blur, LooksRare — respect when distributing secondary sale proceeds. Artists set their royalty percentage (typically 10–15%) at the time of minting, and that royalty is permanently encoded in the contract. When a buyer resells the NFT on any ERC-2981-compatible marketplace, the royalty is automatically distributed to the artist's wallet without any intermediary.",
    "Artwork files are stored on IPFS via Pinata's pinning service, with the content-addressed IPFS hash permanently recorded on-chain in the token metadata. This means artwork cannot be swapped out after minting — the hash is immutable. We also store a high-resolution version of the artwork alongside a watermarked preview, with access to the full resolution gated by token ownership verification via wallet signature. This was an important design decision for artists concerned about unauthorised reproduction.",
    "We chose Polygon PoS as the deployment network. At the time of deployment, gas costs for minting on Polygon were running at fractions of a cent compared to $20–80 on Ethereum mainnet. For a collective selling limited editions at $200–$2,000, the difference was the viability of the entire project. We built a bridge guide into the platform help documentation explaining how buyers could move funds from Ethereum mainnet to Polygon, which was the most common point of friction for international buyers.",
    "The buyer experience was designed for wallet-unfamiliar collectors as much as crypto-native ones. We integrated both MetaMask (for existing wallet holders) and WalletConnect (for mobile wallets) and provided an in-platform guide for creating a first wallet. Fiat on-ramp documentation pointed buyers to MoonPay and Transak. The artist-facing minting UI was simplified to the point where it could be completed in under 10 minutes without technical knowledge — upload artwork, set edition size, set price, set royalty percentage, confirm transaction.",
    "A Node.js backend with PostgreSQL provides off-chain indexing of on-chain events, powering the browsable gallery, artist profile pages, sales history, and royalty earnings dashboard. Listening to contract events via Ethers.js and maintaining a local database meant the frontend could deliver a fast, standard web experience without requiring users to query the blockchain directly for every page load.",
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The project ran over 14 weeks from contract signature to mainnet launch. Smart contract development and testing occupied the first six weeks, running in parallel with the IPFS storage architecture and backend API. The audit was conducted in weeks seven and eight by an independent smart contract security firm — we provided the full test suite, natspec documentation, and a threat model as part of the audit package.",
    "The audit returned with four findings: one medium-severity issue relating to a potential front-running vector on the primary sale price mechanism (fixed by adding a buyer-price-confirmation step), and three low-severity findings around event emission consistency and input validation. All four were resolved before mainnet deployment. The audit report was published in the platform's documentation — transparency about the security posture was important to the collective and their buyers.",
    "Artist onboarding ran across weeks ten and eleven as a staged process. We onboarded a cohort of 15 pilot artists first, working through the minting flow with them individually and collecting feedback. The most common issue was MetaMask not being installed — we introduced a more prominent 'first time here?' onboarding path as a result. We also created video walkthroughs for the minting process that became the most-visited pages in the help centre.",
    "AUSTRAC registration was handled by the client as a business decision with their legal advisors. We provided technical documentation describing the platform's transaction flows, wallet interactions and any fiat off-ramp integrations to support their AML/CTF compliance assessment. We were clear throughout the project that AUSTRAC registration obligations for digital currency exchange depend on how the platform is classified under the AML/CTF Act 2006, and that this was a legal determination, not a technical one.",
    "Mainnet launch was a soft launch to the collective's existing mailing list before any public announcement. This gave us a production stress test with a friendly audience and surfaced two minor UI issues with mobile wallet connections on iOS. Both were fixed within 48 hours. The public launch followed two weeks later with a press release targeted at Australian arts media, which generated coverage in several digital art and creative industry publications.",
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The legal pre-work was not optional — it was foundational. Projects that skip the regulatory assessment upfront either launch with legal uncertainty hanging over them, or have to pause mid-build when the questions can no longer be avoided. Adding two weeks and a legal fee before writing code was the right call, and every similar project we take on now has this as a non-negotiable first step.",
    "Wallet UX remains the single biggest adoption barrier for non-crypto-native audiences, and it cannot be solved by better copy alone. The 'first wallet' experience — installing an extension, securing a seed phrase, acquiring cryptocurrency, bridging to the right network — is genuinely complex for people unfamiliar with it. We built significant onboarding support into this project, and we still saw drop-off. Future projects in this space need to seriously evaluate account abstraction (ERC-4337 smart contract wallets) or fiat-first on-ramp integrations as a way to abstract this complexity away.",
    "ERC-2981 royalty enforcement depends on marketplace compliance, not protocol enforcement. Major marketplaces have moved toward optional royalties in certain trading contexts to compete on fees. Artists should be counselled upfront that on-chain royalties are a signal, not a guarantee, and that their enforceability varies by platform. This is a real limitation of the current NFT royalty ecosystem that we now communicate clearly in scoping conversations.",
    "IPFS pinning via a single service provider introduces a dependency risk. If Pinata were to cease operations or end the pinning arrangement, the metadata links on-chain would break. We now recommend clients either maintain their own IPFS node, use redundant pinning services, or consider Arweave for permanent decentralised storage on high-value collections.",
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Following the successful launch, the collective commissioned a second phase of development focused on physical artwork provenance. The plan involved embedding NFC chips into physical prints that would link back to the corresponding NFT, creating a dual physical-digital provenance record. This work is ongoing.",
    "Several individual artists from the collective approached us separately about more ambitious drops — larger edition sizes, timed auctions, and integration with broader Australian NFT marketplaces. We assisted two of them with contract customisations for Dutch auction mechanics and phased reveal functionality.",
    "The collective's experience has made them active advocates in the Melbourne arts community for sober, technically grounded conversations about NFTs. The director has spoken at two industry events about the importance of getting legal and technical advice before committing to blockchain platforms.",
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "In the first three months after public launch, the platform generated $340,000 in primary sales across all 85 artists. The shift from a 50% gallery commission to a 2.5% platform fee fundamentally changed artists' economics — an artist selling $10,000 worth of editions now retains $9,750 instead of $5,000. On-chain royalties from secondary market resales generated $18,400 in artist income in the same period — revenue that would have been completely invisible under the previous gallery arrangement. Twelve international buyers from eight countries completed purchases, with average transaction confirmation times under 30 seconds on Polygon. The platform has not experienced any security incidents since launch.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "$340K", label: "Primary sales in first 3 months", context: "Across all 85 artists post-launch" },
    { value: "2.5%", label: "Platform fee vs 50% gallery commission", context: "Artists retain 97.5% of primary sale proceeds" },
    { value: "$18,400", label: "On-chain royalty income generated", context: "From secondary market resales — was $0 previously" },
    { value: "85", label: "Artists fully onboarded", context: "Including non-technical members in their 60s" },
    { value: "12", label: "International buyers from 8 countries", context: "US, UK, Germany, Singapore and others" },
    { value: "0", label: "Security incidents post-audit", context: "All 4 audit findings resolved pre-launch" },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "Solidity (ERC-721 + ERC-2981)", reason: "ERC-721 for unique token identity per edition; ERC-2981 for on-chain royalty signalling compatible with major secondary marketplaces" },
    { name: "Polygon PoS", reason: "Sub-cent gas fees made $200–$2,000 artwork editions economically viable — Ethereum mainnet gas would have consumed unacceptable margins" },
    { name: "Hardhat", reason: "Development environment and testing framework; 94 unit tests covering mint paths, royalties, edge cases and reentrancy" },
    { name: "IPFS / Pinata", reason: "Content-addressed, immutable artwork storage — IPFS hash recorded on-chain ensures artwork cannot be swapped post-mint" },
    { name: "React", reason: "Gallery frontend, artist minting dashboard and buyer purchase flow; optimised for both wallet-connected and first-time visitors" },
    { name: "Ethers.js", reason: "Wallet interaction layer for MetaMask and WalletConnect integration; contract event listening for off-chain indexing" },
    { name: "MetaMask / WalletConnect", reason: "Dual wallet integration covers both browser extension users and mobile wallet holders" },
    { name: "Node.js + PostgreSQL", reason: "Off-chain event indexing for fast gallery browsing, artist profiles, sales history and royalty dashboard without requiring live blockchain queries" },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "DeFi Yield Aggregator",
      href: "/case-studies/defi-yield-aggregator",
      industry: "Web3 & Crypto",
      summary: "Audited, gas-optimised smart contracts automatically moving user funds between yield protocols, reaching $4.2M TVL within 60 days of mainnet launch.",
    },
    {
      title: "Tokenised Real World Asset Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/tokenised-real-world-assets",
      industry: "Web3 & Crypto",
      summary: "Fractional property investment via security tokens for a Sydney property investment company, navigating ASIC MIS requirements and KYC obligations.",
    },
    {
      title: "DAO Governance Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/dao-governance-platform",
      industry: "Web3 & Crypto",
      summary: "On-chain governance and treasury management for an Australian DAO with 1,200 token holders, increasing participation from 12% to 53%.",
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: "Smart Contract Development", href: "/services/smart-contract-development" },
    { title: "Web3 Frontend Development", href: "/services/web3-frontend-development" },
    { title: "Smart Contract Audit Support", href: "/services/smart-contract-audit-support" },
    { title: "Blockchain Consulting", href: "/services/blockchain-consulting" },
  ],
};
